"""
MKT Context Commentary — Mark chapters 12–13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-mark-12-13.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/mark.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/mark.json
- data/commentary/mkt-context/mark.json (existing; 12:13 and 13:1 already present)

Key decisions in this range:
- Parable of the Tenants: Isa 5:1-7 (Song of the Vineyard) identified as the primary
  template; absentee-landlord tenant farming documented from Galilean economic history
- Tax trap: Tiberius denarius inscription reproduced; Roman/Herodian political dynamics
- Sadducees: Josephus confirms they denied resurrection; levirate marriage per Deut 25
- Great Commandment: Shema (Deut 6:4-5) twice-daily recitation context; Hillel parallel
- Widow's mite: temple gazophylakion trumpet-chests in Court of Women documented
- Ch 13 (Olivet Discourse): Mark written ca. 65-70 CE — this discourse addresses a
  community facing real persecution. Abomination of desolation traced from Dan 9:27
  / Antiochus IV Epiphanes through 70 CE application. Cosmic-sign language (vv.24-25)
  treated as conventional prophetic judgment vocabulary (OT parallels cited), not
  literal astronomy. "This generation" (v.30) primary referent = people alive in
  Jesus's time; 70 CE fulfillment the lexically natural reading. Four Roman night
  watches (v.35) noted as foreshadowing the passion narrative timeline in chs.14-16.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK_CH12_13 = {
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>The vineyard image is drawn directly from Isa 5:1-7 (the Song of the Vineyard), which every literate Jewish listener would recognize immediately: a vineyard with a wall, a winepress, and a watchtower precisely matching Isaiah&rsquo;s description. Palestinian vineyards were enclosed with stone-rubble or thorn-hedge walls; the winepress consisted of two stone vats hewn into bedrock (a treading basin above and a collection vat below); the watchtower (<em>migdal</em>) housed guards during harvest. The parable is not merely an analogy &mdash; it is an extended interpretation of Isaiah&rsquo;s allegory, relocated to first-century Jerusalem&rsquo;s temple controversy.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Absentee-landlord tenant farming was the dominant agricultural system in first-century Galilee. Many peasant families had lost ancestral land to debt during the economic disruptions of Hasmonean and Herodian administration and now worked as tenant farmers paying rents in kind &mdash; a fixed share of the harvest. The Mishnah and Egyptian papyri document sharecropping (<em>aris</em>) arrangements with rents typically between one-third and one-half of the yield. The owner&rsquo;s sending of a servant at harvest time to collect his portion was the normal landlord action; the tenants&rsquo; response is not.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The beating and empty-handed dismissal of the first servant activates the prophetic tradition of Israel&rsquo;s rejection of God&rsquo;s messengers. Neh 9:26 summarizes: &ldquo;They killed your prophets who had warned them in order to turn them back to you.&rdquo; Jer 7:25-26 uses the same pattern: God sends his servants the prophets again and again, and Israel does not listen. The parable&rsquo;s escalation through multiple servants maps this historical pattern onto the tenants&rsquo; repeated refusals.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The escalation from beating and dismissal to striking on the head and shameful treatment follows the pattern of increasing severity in the prophetic-rejection motif. &ldquo;Treated him shamefully&rdquo; (<em>ētimassan</em>) is the language of public dishonoring &mdash; in an honor-shame culture, shaming a representative was shaming the one who sent him. The owner continues to send envoys despite the growing violence, which is itself a characterization of divine patience toward Israel.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The accumulation of servants who are beaten or killed captures the full sweep of prophetic history in compressed form. Jewish tradition had developed a theology of the murdered prophets: Jer 2:30, 1 Kgs 19:10 (&ldquo;they have killed your prophets with the sword&rdquo;), and the tradition that Isaiah was sawn in two (preserved in Mart. Isa. and referenced in Heb 11:37). The killing of prophets was not a later theological construction but a recognized pattern that Jesus&rsquo;s contemporaries acknowledged as their history (cf. Matt 23:29-37).</p>',
    "6": '<p>The owner&rsquo;s sending of his &ldquo;beloved son&rdquo; (<em>huion agapēton</em>) as the final messenger echoes the divine voice at Jesus&rsquo;s baptism (1:11) and Transfiguration (9:7): &ldquo;This is my Son, the Beloved.&rdquo; The owner&rsquo;s reasoning &mdash; &ldquo;they will respect my son&rdquo; &mdash; creates dramatic irony: the audience knows what the tenants will do, just as they have seen what Jerusalem&rsquo;s leadership is plotting against Jesus as he tells the parable in the temple precincts.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The tenants&rsquo; reasoning &mdash; &ldquo;this is the heir; come, let&rsquo;s kill him, and the inheritance will be ours&rdquo; &mdash; reflects a known element of Roman property law. Under certain conditions, if a property owner died without heirs, occupiers could claim the land after a waiting period. Whether or not the tenants&rsquo; legal reasoning was sound, the parable presents them as acting on the belief that killing the heir would leave the vineyard claimable. The detail that they threw him out of the vineyard after killing (v.8) may carry typological weight: Jesus would be crucified outside Jerusalem&rsquo;s walls (John 19:20; Heb 13:12).</p>',
    "8": '<p>The throwing out of the vineyard after killing completes the inversion: the heir, who should inherit everything, is cast out as if he were the intruder. The sequence &mdash; killed, then thrown out &mdash; also reverses proper burial. In Jewish culture, proper burial was a sacred obligation; to deny it was the ultimate indignity (cf. Jer 22:18-19). The parable&rsquo;s audience in the temple courts understood the full weight of the allusion to an unburied body cast outside the estate.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The rhetorical question and its answer predict judgment on the tenants and the transfer of the vineyard to others. For the original audience, &ldquo;others&rdquo; could mean the common people of Israel in contrast to the Jerusalem leadership, or Gentiles &mdash; the Gentile-mission reading is picked up by Mark&rsquo;s explicitly Gentile audience, for whom the transfer of covenant privilege to include them is the Gospel&rsquo;s explicit theme. The chief priests and scribes, who understand the parable is about them (v.12), interpret the threat correctly.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Ps 118:22-23 &mdash; the rejected stone that becomes the cornerstone &mdash; was one of the most influential Christological proof texts in early Christianity (Acts 4:11; 1 Pet 2:7; Eph 2:20). Psalm 118 was among the Hallel Psalms (113-118) sung at Passover; the Jerusalem crowds had just cried its verses during Jesus&rsquo;s entry (11:9: &ldquo;Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord&rdquo; = Ps 118:26). The psalm was fresh in every listener&rsquo;s memory in the week before Passover.</p>',
    "11": '<p>&ldquo;This is the Lord&rsquo;s doing and it is marvelous in our eyes&rdquo; (Ps 118:23) names the reversal as a divine act, not a human achievement. The stone&rsquo;s elevation from rejection to cornerstone is not a natural social reversal but a specific act of God. The citation transforms the parable&rsquo;s ending from a prediction of judgment to a proclamation of vindication &mdash; the son who is killed becomes the stone that defines the new structure.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The authorities&rsquo; desire to arrest Jesus but their fear of the crowd illustrates the social dynamics of honor-shame politics. Arresting a popular figure in public risked crowd violence; their power was contingent on the crowd&rsquo;s acquiescence. This is the same restraint that prevented them from challenging John the Baptist publicly (11:31-32). The charge that &ldquo;he had spoken the parable against them&rdquo; shows their interpretive competence &mdash; they are not confused about the meaning; they are furious because of it.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The question about taxes (v.13-17) was a political trap with no safe answer in the Roman-occupied Jewish context: affirming Caesar\'s tax alienated Jewish nationalists; denying it risked arrest for sedition. The denarius bore the image and inscription of Tiberius Caesar (TIBERIVS CAESAR DIVI AVGVSTI FILIVS AVGVSTVS) with the reverse PONTIF MAXIM. For strict Jews, carrying such an idolatrous image in the temple precinct was itself questionable; the fact that the questioners had one ready reveals their own accommodation to Rome. Jesus\'s answer distinguishes what belongs to Caesar from what belongs to God, leaving the deeper question of who owns the human person unanswered on the surface.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The elaborate flattery (&ldquo;you aren&rsquo;t swayed by others&rdquo;) is a rhetorical setup designed to make evasion socially impossible. The question concerns the <em>kēnsos</em> (poll tax, Latin <em>census</em>) &mdash; the direct tribute paid to Rome, a fixed per-head tax levied since Roman annexation of Judea in 6 CE. This tax sparked the revolt of Judas the Galilean in that year (Josephus Ant. 18.4-10), who declared payment was tantamount to acknowledging Caesar as master and incompatible with the exclusive lordship of God. The question thus carried the memory of an armed rebellion and its consequences.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Jesus&rsquo;s demand to see the coin is a masterstroke of counter-rhetoric: by asking them to produce it, he reveals that they already carry the Roman coin they are questioning him about. They are participants in the Roman economy whose legitimacy they are asking him to adjudicate. &ldquo;Knowing their hypocrisy&rdquo; (<em>hupokrisis</em> = the performance of a role, wearing a mask) is Mark&rsquo;s editorial note: the questioners perform sincerity while constructing a trap.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The coin produced is most likely a Tiberian denarius bearing the bust of Tiberius (emperor 14-37 CE) with the legend TIBERIVS CAESAR DIVI AVGVSTI FILIVS AVGVSTVS (&ldquo;Tiberius Caesar, son of the divine Augustus, Augustus&rdquo;) and on the reverse the seated figure with the legend PONTIF MAXIM (&ldquo;Pontifex Maximus,&rdquo; the Roman high-priestly title). The divine titulature (&ldquo;son of the divine Augustus&rdquo;) was blasphemous in Jewish ears; producing this coin in the temple precincts makes the irony pointed.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Jesus&rsquo;s answer separates the domains of Caesar and God without simply ranking them. Caesar&rsquo;s image on the coin means the coin belongs in his system &mdash; return it. Humans bear the image of God (Gen 1:26-27) &mdash; what belongs to God is the person, not just money. The implication is that the questioner&rsquo;s framing was too narrow: the real question is not which coin to pay but who owns the human being. The crowd&rsquo;s amazement signals recognition that the answer has escaped the trap entirely.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The Sadducees were the priestly aristocracy of Jerusalem, centered on the high-priestly families and temple administration. Unlike the Pharisees, they accepted only the written Torah (Pentateuch) and rejected oral tradition and doctrines not explicitly in it &mdash; including resurrection, which appears explicitly only in Daniel 12:2, Isaiah 26:19, and Ezekiel 37. Josephus confirms their denial of bodily resurrection (War 2.165; Ant. 18.16). Their approach uses a reductio ad absurdum from Pentateuchal law rather than a political trap.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Levirate marriage (<em>yibbum</em>) is prescribed in Deut 25:5-10: if a man dies without sons, his brother must marry the widow to preserve the dead brother&rsquo;s name and inheritance. The Hebrew root is <em>yabam</em> (brother-in-law). The institution protected widows from destitution and preserved family land in a society where both were otherwise at risk; the Mishnah later regulated it extensively (tractate Yevamot). The Sadducees construct their test case on this unambiguous Torah prescription.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The hypothetical of seven brothers sequentially marrying one widow is a reductio ad absurdum, a form familiar from both Greek philosophical logic and Jewish legal debate. Seven is the number of completeness in Hebrew symbolism &mdash; the scenario exhausts the possibilities. The Sadducees are not asking about a real case but constructing a logical impossibility to demonstrate that resurrection leads to irresolvable legal contradictions within Torah law itself.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Each brother fulfilling the levirate obligation while dying without children maintains the legal integrity of the scenario &mdash; each marriage was valid under Torah, no adultery occurred, no divorce happened. The Sadducees are building a legally clean test case that cannot be dismissed on procedural grounds. Their point is that resurrection creates a situation Torah cannot adjudicate &mdash; and since Torah is God&rsquo;s complete revelation, this impossibility disproves the doctrine.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The death of the woman last closes the scenario and makes the rhetorical point inescapable: seven valid marriages have occurred in sequence, all parties are now dead, and resurrection will presumably require legal adjudication of the marital status. The scenario rests on the assumption that resurrection restores the same social relationships and legal institutions that existed in this life &mdash; an assumption Jesus will directly challenge in his response.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The question &ldquo;at the resurrection whose wife will she be?&rdquo; is the logical conclusion the Sadducees have been building toward: if resurrection restores earthly conditions, then seven valid marital claims on one woman is an impossibility. Their argument is internally coherent within its premises. Jesus&rsquo;s response will deny the premises &mdash; the resurrection state is not a restoration of earthly conditions &mdash; rather than working within their framework to solve the puzzle.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Jesus identifies two compounding errors: ignorance of the scriptures and ignorance of the power of God. Accusing the Sadducees &mdash; the educated priestly aristocracy &mdash; of scriptural ignorance was a sharp reversal of expected social roles. &ldquo;The power of God&rdquo; refers specifically to God&rsquo;s capacity to reconstitute human existence in a mode qualitatively different from earthly existence &mdash; something the Sadducees&rsquo; materialist framework cannot accommodate.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The resurrected state as &ldquo;like the angels&rdquo; draws on Second Temple angelology: angels were understood as non-reproducing spiritual beings not subject to death. 1 Enoch and other Second Temple texts describe angels as neither marrying nor being given in marriage, existing in a permanent, non-generative mode. The point is not that the resurrected become angels but that resurrection transforms the conditions of existence: institutions developed for this age (marriage for bearing children and economic stability) are not carried unchanged into the age to come.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Jesus&rsquo;s counter-argument uses the burning bush narrative (Exod 3:6) &mdash; an impeccably Pentateuchal source, since the Sadducees accepted only the Torah. God says &ldquo;I am [present tense] the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob&rdquo; &mdash; not &ldquo;I was.&rdquo; The present-tense divine claim implies these patriarchs are living realities before God at the moment of speaking, not merely historical figures. Argument from verbal tense was a recognized exegetical form in Jewish legal debate and would have been familiar to any educated audience.</p>',
    "27": '<p>&ldquo;He is not the God of the dead but of the living&rdquo; reformulates the burning bush argument: if God says &ldquo;I AM the God of Abraham,&rdquo; and God is the God of the living (not the dead), then Abraham must be living. The conclusion directly refutes the Sadducean position using their own canonical source. &ldquo;You are badly mistaken&rdquo; (<em>polu planasthe</em>) is among Jesus&rsquo;s most direct condemnations in any of the controversy dialogues of Mark&rsquo;s Jerusalem section.</p>',
    "28": '<p>Unlike the previous questioners (Pharisees + Herodians in v.13; Sadducees in v.18), Mark&rsquo;s scribe approaches with genuine interest: &ldquo;noticing that Jesus had given them a good answer.&rdquo; Matthew&rsquo;s parallel (22:34-40) makes the question a test, but Mark&rsquo;s framing presents real theological inquiry, and the dialogue ends with mutual recognition (v.34). The question &ldquo;which commandment is the most important of all?&rdquo; was a recognized debate in rabbinic tradition &mdash; the attempt to identify the principle from which the rest of Torah could be derived.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The Shema (Deut 6:4-5) was the central confession of Jewish faith, recited twice daily &mdash; at dawn and at dusk &mdash; as a religious obligation from at least the Second Temple period. Its opening word &ldquo;Hear&rdquo; (<em>shema</em>) is programmatic: the covenant relationship is constituted by attentive receptive listening followed by responsive love. Mark&rsquo;s Jesus quotes the full introduction (&ldquo;The Lord our God, the Lord is one&rdquo;) before the command &mdash; uniquely among the Synoptics &mdash; grounding the love-command in the monotheistic confession.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The four-dimensional formulation of love &mdash; heart, soul, mind, strength &mdash; renders the Hebrew <em>levav/nephesh/me&rsquo;od</em> of Deut 6:5 using Greek psychological vocabulary. The Hebrew <em>me&rsquo;od</em> (very much, strength) becomes <em>ischys</em> (physical strength); <em>levav</em> (the inner decision-making center) becomes <em>kardia</em> (heart); <em>nephesh</em> (life-breath, whole self) becomes <em>psychē</em>. The addition of &ldquo;mind&rdquo; (<em>dianoia</em>) as a fourth category reflects Hellenistic psychological categories integrated with the Deuteronomic summons to total, undivided orientation toward God.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Lev 19:18 (&ldquo;love your neighbor as yourself&rdquo;) comes from the Holiness Code within a cluster of social-justice commands concerning gleaning for the poor, honest wages, impartiality in judgment, and care for the foreigner (Lev 19:9-18). The conjunction of these two commands was not unique to Jesus: Hillel famously summarized the Torah as &ldquo;What is hateful to you, do not do to your neighbor; that is the whole Torah, and the rest is commentary&rdquo; (b. Shab. 31a). The combination of Deut 6 and Lev 19 as a double summary appears in T. Iss. 5:2 and T. Dan 5:3 as well, suggesting a tradition Jesus shares and affirms.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The scribe&rsquo;s response &mdash; &ldquo;well said, teacher&rdquo; &mdash; quotes Jesus&rsquo;s answer approvingly and adds a gloss: loving God and neighbor &ldquo;is worth more than all burnt offerings and sacrifices.&rdquo; This echoes Hos 6:6 (&ldquo;I desire mercy and not sacrifice&rdquo;) and 1 Sam 15:22 (&ldquo;to obey is better than sacrifice&rdquo;). The scribe, as a teacher of the law tied to the temple system, here relativizes the sacrificial cult in favor of the ethical command &mdash; a significant move that aligns him with the prophetic reform tradition.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The scribe&rsquo;s elaboration uses &ldquo;heart, understanding, and strength&rdquo; rather than the full four-fold formula of v.30 &mdash; a variation that may reflect oral tradition or his own phrasing. The key addition is the explicit priority claim: the love commandment exceeds the cultic system in value. In the temple precincts, during Passover week, from a teacher of the law, this is a striking theological statement: the institution surrounding him matters less than what he has just affirmed.</p>',
    "34": '<p>&ldquo;You are not far from the kingdom of God&rdquo; is the highest praise Jesus extends to any interlocutor in Mark. &ldquo;Not far&rdquo; (<em>ou makran</em>) is genuine proximity without full arrival: the scribe has grasped what the kingdom requires but has not yet entered it through following Jesus. The conversation silences all further public questions &mdash; &ldquo;no one dared to ask him any more questions&rdquo; &mdash; suggesting that the quality and authority of Jesus&rsquo;s teaching has exhausted the attempts to test or entrap him.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The scribal teaching that the Messiah is &ldquo;the Son of David&rdquo; rests on 2 Sam 7:12-16 (God&rsquo;s promise to David of an eternal throne) and its development in Isa 11:1-10 and Ps 89:3-4. The title &ldquo;Son of David&rdquo; was a recognized Messianic designation in Second Temple Judaism (Psalms of Solomon 17:21: &ldquo;Raise up for them their king, the son of David&rdquo;). Jesus&rsquo;s counter-question does not deny Davidic descent but complicates what it entails &mdash; a son who is also Lord exceeds the merely political category.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Ps 110:1 &mdash; &ldquo;The LORD [YHWH] said to my Lord [Adonai]: &lsquo;Sit at my right hand until I put your enemies under your feet&rsquo;&rdquo; &mdash; was the most cited OT passage in the NT (Acts 2:34-35; Heb 1:13; 1 Cor 15:25). Jesus quotes the LXX form. The attribution to David &ldquo;speaking by the Holy Spirit&rdquo; reflects standard Jewish understanding that David composed the Psalms under prophetic inspiration (2 Sam 23:2; Acts 2:30). If David composed Ps 110 and addresses its subject as &ldquo;my Lord,&rdquo; then the Messiah holds a position of exaltation that David himself honors.</p>',
    "37": '<p>The logical puzzle is sharp: if David calls the Messiah &ldquo;Lord,&rdquo; then the Messiah&rsquo;s relationship to David is not simply that of son to father &mdash; which would require the son to honor the father, not the reverse. The question does not deny Davidic descent but forces a rethinking of what &ldquo;Son of David&rdquo; means when David himself ascribes to the Messiah a position of exaltation at God&rsquo;s right hand. &ldquo;The large crowd listened to him with delight&rdquo; &mdash; scribal debate of this quality was popular, and Jesus has clearly won the exchange on its own terms.</p>',
    "38": '<p>The &ldquo;long robes&rdquo; (<em>stolai</em>) were the distinctive dress of scribal teachers &mdash; long linen robes marking their status as men of learning. The marketplace greeting was an honor transaction: the proper title, depth of bow, and number of honorifics publicly displayed the relative honor of both parties. Scribes expected the deferential greetings their social position commanded; receiving them in public spaces reinforced their prestige in the community&rsquo;s eyes. The social performance of honor was as essential as the substance of learning.</p>',
    "39": '<p>The most important seats in the synagogue were the front benches facing the congregation, where teachers and honored elders sat visible to the whole assembly. These seats were prominent and gave the occupant a leading role in synagogue proceedings. At banquets, the Greco-Roman <em>triclinium</em> placed guests on three sides of a U-shaped table; position at the right hand of the host was highest honor. Scribes who angled for these positions were participating in the honor-competition system Jesus has been critiquing since 9:34, now applied to its most religious expression.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The charge of &ldquo;devouring widows&rsquo; houses&rdquo; is specific: scribes served as estate managers, legal trustees, and will-executors for patrons, including widows without male family members. The accusation is that they exploited positions of legal trust to transfer property to themselves or charge excessive fees. The &ldquo;lengthy prayers for a show&rdquo; makes the spiritual pretension complicit in the financial exploitation &mdash; public piety used as cover for private predation. &ldquo;Most severely&rdquo; (<em>perissoteron krima</em>) inverts the honor they seek: the greater the pretension, the greater the judgment that awaits.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The temple treasury (<em>gazophylakion</em>) in the Court of Women had thirteen trumpet-shaped (<em>shofar</em>-shaped) collection receptacles, each labeled for a different purpose: oil for the lamps, wood for the altar fires, gold for incense, and the various designated purposes of the half-shekel tax. The trumpet shape meant the sound of coins dropping in could be heard across the court &mdash; large donations produced a more impressive sound. Jesus&rsquo;s sustained seated observation opposite the treasury is deliberate &mdash; he is paying close attention to the giving patterns of those passing by.</p>',
    "42": '<p>The <em>lepton</em> (from Greek <em>leptos</em>, thin) was the smallest Greek bronze coin in circulation; two <em>lepta</em> equaled one Roman <em>quadrans</em> &mdash; the smallest Roman coin, worth one-quarter of an <em>as</em>, approximately one sixty-fourth of a denarius (a day laborer&rsquo;s daily wage was one denarius). Mark&rsquo;s explanation of the coin value for his Gentile audience is one of his characteristic editorial clarifications for non-Jewish readers (cf. 7:3-4, 15:42), confirming the Gentile setting of his Gospel.</p>',
    "43": '<p>Jesus&rsquo;s evaluation of the widow&rsquo;s gift reverses the honor-culture calculus of benefaction. In the Greco-Roman system of <em>euergetism</em> (public benefaction), the size of the gift determined the donor&rsquo;s honor: large gifts funded temples, games, and public buildings and earned inscribed dedications and reserved seats at civic events. The widow&rsquo;s two coins are invisible within this framework. Jesus reframes the evaluation entirely around what is given relative to what one has &mdash; percentage rather than absolute amount &mdash; which is a radical departure from the honor economy.</p>',
    "44": '<p>The contrast between giving out of surplus (<em>ek tou perisseuontos</em>) and giving out of poverty (<em>ek tēs hysterēseōs</em>) exposes the economic reality beneath the religious display. The wealthy who give visibly from their abundance experience no change in material security; the widow gives from what she needed for food. <em>Holon ton bion autēs</em> (&ldquo;her whole life/livelihood&rdquo;) uses <em>bios</em>, which means both &ldquo;life&rdquo; and &ldquo;means of living&rdquo; &mdash; she gives her life in the most material sense. Placed immediately before Jesus&rsquo;s prediction of the temple&rsquo;s destruction (13:2), the scene raises the unsettling question of whether the institution that has just consumed this widow&rsquo;s last resources deserves the devotion it commands.</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>The temple complex that Jesus predicts will be destroyed (not one stone upon another, v.2) was indeed dismantled by Titus\'s forces in 70 CE; Josephus records the systematic destruction (War 6.4.5-7.1.1). The Olivet Discourse (ch.13) addresses the conflation of Jerusalem\'s destruction with the end of the age — a natural mistake given that both were expected simultaneously in Jewish eschatology. Mark\'s Olivet Discourse reflects a community experiencing real persecution (v.9: councils, synagogues, governors, kings) consistent with the Neronian context or the Jewish War period.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Herod&rsquo;s temple was considered one of the wonders of the ancient world. Josephus describes limestone blocks approximately 22.5 meters long, 3 meters high, and 3 meters wide, fitted without mortar (War 5.5.1-6; Ant. 15.392-402); Tacitus marvels at its construction (Hist. 5.8). The destruction by Titus&rsquo;s forces in 70 CE fulfilled the prediction precisely: Josephus records that the entire structure was dismantled to its foundations (War 7.1.1). The Western Wall visible today is part of the retaining wall of the temple platform, not the temple building itself &mdash; no stone of the building remains on another.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The Mount of Olives rises directly east of the temple, separated from it by the Kidron Valley. From its upper slopes, the entire western face of the temple complex was fully visible. This is the first time in Mark that Peter, James, John, and Andrew are named together as a group since their original call (1:16-20). Their private inquiry with Jesus signals a shift from public temple teaching to inner-circle eschatological instruction, following the pattern already established in Mark (4:10; 7:17; 9:28): private space yields private revelation.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The disciples&rsquo; double question &mdash; &ldquo;when will these things happen?&rdquo; and &ldquo;what will be the sign?&rdquo; &mdash; conflates two events that were expected to be simultaneous in Jewish eschatology: the destruction of Jerusalem and the end of the age. Apocalyptic texts written after 70 CE (4 Ezra, 2 Baruch) demonstrate how naturally first-century Jews linked the two. Jesus&rsquo;s answer partly addresses the conflation by distinguishing events: Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall (which can be anticipated from signs) from the final day (whose timing is unknown even to the Son, v.32).</p>',
    "5": '<p>The opening command &ldquo;watch out that no one deceives you&rdquo; (<em>blepete mē tis hymas planēsē</em>) sets the epistemological key of the entire discourse: the primary danger the disciples face is not persecution (which is coming, vv.9-13) but being misled about the meaning and timing of events. The discourse is as much about correct interpretation as about prediction &mdash; it equips the disciples to resist premature eschatological conclusions and false messianic claims in a period of catastrophic crisis.</p>',
    "6": '<p>In the Jewish War period (66-70 CE), multiple figures arose claiming messianic authority and divine commission. Josephus identifies several: Theudas (Ant. 20.97-99), the Egyptian prophet (Ant. 20.169-172; Acts 21:38), Simon bar Giora, and John of Gischala. The claim &ldquo;I am he&rdquo; (<em>ego eimi</em>) may echo the divine name of Exod 3:14 &mdash; a direct messianic or divine self-claim. The destruction of Jerusalem generated exactly the conditions Jesus describes: charismatic leaders, desperate crowds, and messianic expectations inflamed by catastrophe.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Wars and rumors of wars are the first item in the standard Jewish apocalyptic inventory of end-time signs (4 Ezra 13:30-31; 2 Bar 70:2-7; Sib. Or. 3:663-668). The command &ldquo;do not be alarmed&rdquo; (<em>mē throeisthe</em>) is crucial: these events are part of necessary unfolding (&ldquo;these things must happen&rdquo; &mdash; the divine <em>dei</em> of providential necessity) but are not the end itself. The disciples must learn to witness extreme historical violence without concluding that the final moment has arrived prematurely.</p>',
    "8": '<p>&ldquo;Nation against nation, kingdom against kingdom&rdquo; echoes Isa 19:2 and 2 Chr 15:6. Earthquakes and famines are standard elements of OT prophetic judgment oracles. &ldquo;The beginning of birth pangs&rdquo; translates the Jewish technical term <em>chevlei hamashiach</em> (birth pangs of the Messiah) &mdash; the period of intensifying tribulation preceding the new age, like the contractions that precede birth. The metaphor is deliberately hopeful: birth pangs have a goal; they announce arrival, not only suffering.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The persecution prediction is specific and matches early Christian experience: local Jewish councils (the sanhedrins of individual synagogue communities), synagogue flogging (Paul attests receiving &ldquo;forty lashes minus one&rdquo; five times, 2 Cor 11:24), and Roman provincial courts (governors = prefects or procurators; kings = client rulers like Herod Agrippa). The phrase &ldquo;on account of me&rdquo; identifies Christian witness as the reason for the trials, making the trials themselves opportunities for testimony before the very authorities doing the judging.</p>',
    "10": '<p>&ldquo;The gospel must first be preached to all nations&rdquo; inserts a programmatic mission statement into the apocalyptic sequence: the universal proclamation of the gospel is a necessary precondition before the end arrives. This matches Paul&rsquo;s theology in Rom 11:25-26 (the &ldquo;full number of the Gentiles&rdquo; must come in) and the commission of Acts 1:8 (witness to the ends of the earth). Mark&rsquo;s Gentile audience would hear this as making their own inclusion part of the eschatological plan, not an afterthought.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The promise that the Holy Spirit will provide words in trial reflects the Jewish prophetic tradition of divine speech through chosen vessels (Jer 1:9; Exod 4:12) and anticipates the Johannine Paraclete teaching (John 14:26; 16:13). The instruction &ldquo;do not worry beforehand about what to say&rdquo; is pastoral counsel for a community already experiencing trial situations. &ldquo;It is not you speaking, but the Holy Spirit&rdquo; is a claim about the source of the witness &mdash; the defendants are instruments of a testimony that exceeds their own capacity.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Family betrayal (&ldquo;brother will betray brother to death&rdquo;) echoes Mic 7:6 (&ldquo;a man&rsquo;s enemies are the members of his own household&rdquo;) &mdash; a text describing the breakdown of social trust at Israel&rsquo;s worst historical moments. For Mark&rsquo;s community under Neronian persecution or the Jewish War, family denunciations were a real possibility: Roman procedure incentivized informers, and Christian commitment within mixed households created exactly these fault lines. The citation of Micah grounds the experience in prophetic pattern rather than abandonment.</p>',
    "13": '<p>&ldquo;Everyone will hate you because of me&rdquo; does not promise universal social rejection in normal times but in the specific context of the tribulation described in this discourse. &ldquo;The one who stands firm to the end will be saved&rdquo; (<em>ho de hypomeinas eis telos, houtos sōthēsetai</em>) is the call to endurance (<em>hypomonē</em>) that appears throughout Jewish and early Christian persecution texts (Dan 12:12; Rev 13:10; 14:12). The word <em>sōthēsetai</em> (will be saved) carries the full weight of eschatological deliverance, not merely physical survival.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The &ldquo;abomination that causes desolation&rdquo; (<em>bdelygma tēs erēmōseōs</em>) quotes Dan 9:27; 11:31; 12:11. The original historical referent was Antiochus IV Epiphanes&rsquo;s desecration of the Jerusalem temple in 167 BCE, when he erected an altar to Zeus Olympios in the holy place (1 Macc 1:54; 2 Macc 6:1-5). By Jesus&rsquo;s time, this had become the paradigm for sacrilegious desecration. The parenthetical &ldquo;let the reader understand&rdquo; is a literary signal that the text is encoded &mdash; the reader must decode the contemporary referent, most plausibly the Roman armies or imperial standards planted in the temple precincts in 70 CE.</p>',
    "15": '<p>First-century Palestinian houses in villages and towns typically had flat earthen or stone roofs accessible by an external staircase on the outside of the building. The flat roof served as living space, storage, and sleeping area in warm weather. The urgency of the instruction &mdash; do not go inside to collect anything &mdash; reflects the historical reality of sudden military attack, where the margin between life and flight could be measured in minutes. Josephus describes the speed with which Roman forces moved through Jerusalem&rsquo;s districts in the 70 CE siege, cutting off escape.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Palestinian field workers typically left their outer garment (<em>himation</em>) at the field edge while working, as the heavy cloak impeded labor. The instruction not to turn back for it captures the extremity of the flight imperative: possessions that would normally be worth retrieving must be abandoned. The worker in the field without his cloak is a precise image of ordinary daily life; its use here grounds the apocalyptic instruction in lived agricultural experience, making it immediately concrete to Mark&rsquo;s audience.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The special concern for pregnant women and nursing mothers reflects the physical reality of flight: advanced pregnancy or nursing a newborn made rapid movement through difficult terrain dangerous or impossible. The concern is pastoral, not theological &mdash; the suffering of the vulnerable is acknowledged as particularly acute without being spiritualized. Similar pastoral notes appear in ancient siege literature; the horror of what happens to pregnant women in military sieges was a recognized element of catastrophe that no rhetorical softening could address.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The Palestinian rainy season runs roughly from November to March; winter (<em>cheimōn</em>) brought torrential rains, swollen wadis, and impassable mountain roads. The Jordan River became uncrossable; Judean hill roads turned to mud. Josephus describes the conditions around Jerusalem during the Jewish War in winter as adding physical hardship to siege. The prayer request is concrete and meteorological &mdash; a request for logistical mercy in a specific physical context, not a spiritual abstraction about patience.</p>',
    "19": '<p>&ldquo;Days of distress unequaled from the beginning&rdquo; adapts Dan 12:1 (&ldquo;There will be a time of distress such as has not happened from the beginning of nations until then&rdquo;). Such superlative tribulation language is a conventional feature of apocalyptic and prophetic judgment oracles (Joel 2:2; Exod 9:18) signaling incomparable severity, not necessarily a literal claim about historical comparison. Josephus himself uses similar language about Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall: &ldquo;No other city has suffered such miseries&rdquo; (War 5.10.5).</p>',
    "20": '<p>The idea of divine limitation of the tribulation period for the sake of the elect appears in Jewish apocalyptic: 4 Ezra 4:36-37 speaks of God hastening the appointed times; 2 Bar 20:1-2 describes God cutting short the age for the sake of the righteous. This is not a claim that God causes the tribulation but that God limits its duration. The term &ldquo;elect&rdquo; (<em>eklektoi</em>) is the standard LXX term for God&rsquo;s chosen people, applied here to the Christian community as the continuation of the covenant people in the new age.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The false messiahs in the midst of crisis exploit the desperation of people under siege or persecution. Josephus documents multiple charismatic figures during the Jewish War who led followers into the wilderness or to the temple, promising divine deliverance that never came; thousands died following these leaders (Ant. 20.97-99, 169-172; War 6.283-285). The urgency of &ldquo;do not believe it&rdquo; (<em>mē pisteuete</em>) is proportional to the danger: messianic credulity during a siege was lethal.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The warning that false messiahs will perform &ldquo;signs and wonders&rdquo; (<em>sēmeia kai terata</em>) echoes Deut 13:1-3, where Moses warns that a prophet who performs wonders but leads Israel away from God must not be followed regardless of the signs. The precedent distinguishes authentic divine signs from impressive performances that mislead. &ldquo;If possible&rdquo; (<em>ei dynaton</em>) implies that deceiving the elect is extremely difficult but not impossible &mdash; a serious warning without absolute reassurance of immunity.</p>',
    "23": '<p>&ldquo;I have told you everything ahead of time&rdquo; closes the predictive section of the discourse. In prophetic tradition, advance disclosure served two purposes: it authenticated the prophet (accurate prediction proved divine origin) and it protected the community from panic and misinterpretation when events occurred. The disciples have been given interpretive keys that will allow them to understand their situation when it arrives without concluding either that God has abandoned them or that the end has already come.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The darkening of the sun and moon is standard OT prophetic vocabulary for divine judgment on nations &mdash; applied to Babylon (Isa 13:10: &ldquo;the sun will be dark at its rising, and the moon will not shed its light&rdquo;), to Edom (Isa 34:4), and eschatologically in Joel 2:31 and Amos 8:9. These are not predictions of literal astronomical events but the conventional imagery of total divine judgment, drawn from the creation-day framework in which God commands the luminaries and can command their withdrawal. In OT prophetic usage this language regularly describes historical judgments on specific nations.</p>',
    "25": '<p>&ldquo;Stars will fall from the sky&rdquo; continues the cosmic-judgment vocabulary of Isa 34:4 (&ldquo;all the stars of heaven will be dissolved&rdquo; &mdash; in an oracle against Edom) and may reflect Dan 8:10 (the little horn casting some of the starry host to the ground). &ldquo;The heavenly bodies will be shaken&rdquo; signals the collapse of the created order that only God can accomplish. The cumulative effect of vv.24-25 is total cosmic disruption as the framework for the Son of Man&rsquo;s appearing &mdash; not a literal astronomy lesson but the vocabulary of absolute divine intervention.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Dan 7:13-14 describes &ldquo;one like a son of man&rdquo; coming on the clouds of heaven toward the Ancient of Days &mdash; in Daniel, a movement toward God to receive dominion, glory, and sovereign power. Jesus&rsquo;s application presents this as the vindication of the Son of Man that becomes visible to all (&ldquo;people will see&rdquo;). For the Markan community facing persecution, the message is fundamental: the one who appears defeated in the passion is the figure who receives cosmic authority. The coming in power and glory is the reversal of the apparent defeat.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The gathering of the elect &ldquo;from the four winds, from the ends of the earth to the ends of the heavens&rdquo; draws on Deut 30:4 (God gathering scattered Israel from the furthest reaches), Zech 2:10, and Isa 11:11-12. The geographical totality &mdash; four winds, ends of earth, ends of heavens &mdash; is a merism expressing comprehensive universality: none of the elect will be missed in the final gathering. The use of angels as gathering agents reflects Jewish apocalyptic imagery (4 Ezra 4:36) in which divine messengers execute the eschatological reversal.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The fig tree (<em>sykē</em>) was the most common cultivated fruit tree in Palestine, conspicuously losing its leaves in winter and producing new growth in spring. Unlike the olive or cedar, the fig&rsquo;s seasonal pattern was obvious and regular: the tender twigs and new leaves announced summer&rsquo;s approach with reliable accuracy. The point of the parable is the readability of signs: as the fig tree&rsquo;s seasonal behavior can be interpreted by any observer, so the signs Jesus has described can be read by the discerning community as indicating that &ldquo;it&rdquo; is near.</p>',
    "29": '<p>&ldquo;It is near, right at the door&rdquo; uses the standard Jewish spatial-metaphor for temporal imminence (cf. Jas 5:9: &ldquo;the Judge is standing at the door&rdquo;; Rev 3:20: &ldquo;I stand at the door and knock&rdquo;). The ambiguity of the subject &ldquo;it&rdquo; has generated debate: does it refer to the temple&rsquo;s destruction, the coming of the Son of Man, or the kingdom of God? The discourse&rsquo;s structure suggests the events of vv.5-23 as a whole &mdash; including Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall as the primary set of events &mdash; that announce the approach of the Son of Man&rsquo;s coming in vv.24-27.</p>',
    "30": '<p>&ldquo;This generation (<em>genea</em>) will certainly not pass away until all these things have happened&rdquo; is among the most debated NT verses. The primary options are: (a) the generation alive during Jesus&rsquo;s ministry, consistent with fulfillment in 66-70 CE; (b) the Jewish people as an ethnic entity who survive to see final consummation; (c) the generation that begins to see the signs described. The use of <em>genea</em> elsewhere in Mark (8:12, 38; 9:19) consistently refers to Jesus&rsquo;s contemporaries, making option (a) the lexically natural reading, with &ldquo;all these things&rdquo; primarily denoting the temple&rsquo;s destruction and its associated upheavals.</p>',
    "31": '<p>&ldquo;Heaven and earth will pass away but my words will not&rdquo; grounds the preceding predictions in an authority claim that exceeds all temporal reference points. Heaven and earth are the most permanent elements of created reality in OT thought (Ps 102:25-27; Isa 51:6); Jesus sets his word above them in permanence. This is an implicit divine authority claim &mdash; the Torah was understood as eternally valid because it was God&rsquo;s word; Jesus places his own words at the same or greater level of permanence without citing any external authority.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The admission that &ldquo;no one knows about that day or hour, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son, but only the Father&rdquo; was theologically troubling to later interpreters (it became a major text in the Arian controversy; Athanasius addressed it extensively). In its Markan context, it serves the discourse&rsquo;s primary purpose: precisely because the timing is unknown even to the Son, watchfulness rather than calendrical calculation is the only appropriate response. The authentic limitation expressed here is a warrant for perpetual readiness, not a theological problem to be resolved.</p>',
    "33": '<p>&ldquo;Be on guard! Be alert!&rdquo; (<em>blepete, agrypneite</em>) &mdash; two present-tense imperatives calling for continuous watchfulness. <em>Agrypneō</em> (to be sleepless, to keep watch) was the term for a night sentinel&rsquo;s duty; in a Roman garrison, sleeping on watch was a capital offense. The disciples are given the role of sentinels over a community that does not know when the master will return &mdash; the condition of not knowing the hour is not a reason for relaxed waiting but the precise reason for heightened, continuous vigilance.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The parable of the absent householder distributes specific responsibilities to servants and assigns the doorkeeper a particular watch function. In a wealthy Hellenistic or Roman household, servants had specialized roles: stewards managed finances, footmen carried messages, the doorkeeper (<em>thurōros</em>) controlled access and maintained the night watch. The master&rsquo;s absence without a specified return time is the precise condition of the disciples&rsquo; own situation between Jesus&rsquo;s departure and his return &mdash; a condition requiring faithful continuity in assigned responsibilities.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The four watches of the night &mdash; evening, midnight, cockcrow, and dawn &mdash; are the Roman military division of the night into four equal watches of approximately three hours each. This detail is significant: the passion narrative of Mark 14-15 uses exactly these same time markers (14:17 = evening; 14:35 = around midnight in Gethsemane; 14:72 = cockcrow; 15:1 = early morning / dawn). The Olivet Discourse thus foreshadows the passion chronology: the disciples are told to watch during precisely those hours when they will fall asleep in Gethsemane (14:37-41).</p>',
    "36": '<p>The danger of the master finding the household asleep reflects a real social scenario: an absentee patron returning to find his household in disorder could dismiss the servants immediately. In the parable&rsquo;s eschatological application, &ldquo;finding them sleeping&rdquo; represents the failure of readiness that the entire discourse has been warning against. The surprise of the master&rsquo;s return is the structural point: it cannot be anticipated by calculation and can only be prepared for by consistent, ongoing faithfulness regardless of timing.</p>',
    "37": '<p>&ldquo;What I say to you, I say to everyone: Watch!&rdquo; (<em>gregoreo</em>) broadens the address beyond the four disciples on the Mount of Olives (v.3) to the universal audience of Mark&rsquo;s readers and beyond them. The final imperative summarizes the entire chapter in one word. <em>Gregoreo</em> (to be awake, to watch) echoes Isa 56:10 (Israel&rsquo;s sleeping watchmen), Hab 2:1 (the prophet on his watchtower), and becomes a key term in early Christian paraenesis (1 Thess 5:6; 1 Pet 5:8; Rev 3:2-3). The discourse ends not with a prediction but with a command &mdash; the appropriate response to eschatological uncertainty.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, MARK_CH12_13)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'mark', existing)
    ch12 = len(existing.get('12', {}))
    ch13 = len(existing.get('13', {}))
    print(f'Mark 12: {ch12} verses, Mark 13: {ch13} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
